  "articleBody": "<!-- Page 9 --><article>\n\n\n            <h6 class=\"yellow\">Detail of the decollation of John the Baptist, inside left shutter</h6>\n\n              <p>Memling has enlarged the scene in the foreground of the left shutter: we are in <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">the inner courtyard of Herod's palace</span>.</p>\n              <p>The execution site in the fortress is connected to the palace by <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">a staircase</span> in the background.</p>\n\n            <figure>\n              <picture><source sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-280.webp 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-380.webp 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-480.webp 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-640.webp 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-840.webp 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-1280.webp 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-1600.webp 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-1920.webp 1920w\" type=\"image/webp\"><img src=\"/docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-640.jpg\" title=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the left inner shutter, “the head of John the Baptist”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" alt=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the left inner shutter, “the head of John the Baptist”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" class=\"class-70-img\" width=\"640\" height=\"403\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-280.jpg 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-380.jpg 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-480.jpg 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-640.jpg 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-840.jpg 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-1280.jpg 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-1600.jpg 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/tete_de_baptiste-1920.jpg 1920w\"></picture><figcaption>detail of the left inner shutter, “the head of John the Baptist”</figcaption>\n            </figure>\n\n              <p>To the left of the executioner depicted from behind are the two disciples <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_the_Apostle\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_the_Apostle\" id=\"andre-2\" class=\"yellow\">Andre</a> and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_the_Apostle\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_the_Apostle\" id=\"jean-l-apotre-2\" class=\"yello\">John the Apostle</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n\n            <h6 class=\"yellow\">Memling's inspiration on Van Der Weyden for the scene of the beheading of John the Baptist, inside left shutter</h6>\n\n              \n              <p><span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">The executioner</span> is represented from behind placing <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">the head in the plate</span> presented to him by a barely moved <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salome\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salome\" class=\"yellow\">Salome</a>.</p>\n              <p>Art historians have identified in the positions of the executioner and Salome <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">a reuse by Memling of a similar scene</span> in a work by his master when he was the assistant of this painter in Brussels, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rogier_van_der_Weyden\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rogier_van_der_Weyden\" id=\"rogier-van-der-weyden\" class=\"yellow\">Rogier VAN DER WEYDEN</a>.</p>\n              <p>This is the left inner shutter of the <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\"><cite>Tryptic of St. John</cite></span> painted around <time datetime=\"1450\">1450</time>-<time datetime=\"1455\">55</time> in the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gemäldegalerie,_Berlin\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gemäldegalerie,_Berlin\" id=\"gemaldegalerie\" class=\"yellow\"><ruby lang=\"en\">Painting&nbsp;Gallery<rp>(</rp><rt lang=\"de\">Gemäldegalerie</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></a> of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berlin_State_Museums\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berlin_State_Museums\" id=\"musees-d-etat-de-berlin\" class=\"yellow\"><ruby lang=\"fr\">Berlin&nbsp;State&nbsp;Museums<rp>(</rp><rt lang=\"de\">Staatliche&nbsp;Museen&nbsp;zu&nbsp;Berlin</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></a> <span style=\"color: #999;\">(inventory reference: 534B)</span>.</p>\n\n            <figure>\n              <picture><source sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-280.webp 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-380.webp 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-480.webp 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-640.webp 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-840.webp 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-1280.webp 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-1600.webp 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-1920.webp 1920w\" type=\"image/webp\"><img src=\"/docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-640.jpg\" title=\"Rogier VAN DER WEYDEN, “Triptych of saint John”, detail of the left inner shutter, “Decollation of John the Baptist”, Painting Gallery, Berlin State Museums, Berlin\" alt=\"Rogier VAN DER WEYDEN, “Triptych of saint John”, detail of the left inner shutter, “Decollation of John the Baptist”, Painting Gallery, Berlin State Museums, Berlin\" class=\"class-40-img\" width=\"640\" height=\"1084\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-280.jpg 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-380.jpg 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-480.jpg 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-640.jpg 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-840.jpg 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-1280.jpg 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-1600.jpg 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/triptyque-saint-jean-1920.jpg 1920w\"></picture><figcaption>Rogier VAN DER WEYDEN, “Triptych of saint John”, detail of the left inner shutter, “Decollation of John the Baptist”, Painting Gallery, Berlin State Museums</figcaption>\n            </figure>\n\n\n\n            <h6 class=\"yellow\">Scene of the incineration of the body of John the Baptist in the background, inner central panel</h6>\n\n              <p>Mark's narrative continues: <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\"><q cite=\"https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Bible_(World_English)/Mark#6:29\">When John's disciples heard this, they came and took up his corpse and laid it in a tomb</q></span> <span style=\"color: #999;\">(Mark, chapter 6, verse 29)</span>.</p>\n              <p>According to tradition, this one was taken away from the territories controlled by Herod Antipas, to the West Bank in <ruby style=\"color: #e6a64d;\" lang=\"en\">Sebastee<rp>(</rp><rt style=\"color:#e6a64d;font-size: 70%;letter-spacing: 2px;\" lang=\"grc\">Σεβαστή</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>, the actual village of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sebastia,_Nablus\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sebastia,_Nablus\" id=\"sebastia\" class=\"yellow\"><ruby lang=\"en\">Sebastia<rp>(</rp><rt lang=\"ar\">سبسطية</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></a> and buried with the prophets <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elisha\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elisha\" class=\"yellow\">Elisha</a> and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obadiah\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obadiah\" id=\"abdias\" class=\"yellow\">Abdias</a>.</p>\n\n              <p>On the left of the central panel, on the right, behind John the Baptist, Memling has made this last scene of his legend appear.</p>\n              <p>As his miracles kept occurring at John's burial site, to combat the nascent Christian faith, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_(emperor)\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_(emperor)\" id=\"julien-l-apostat\" class=\"yellow\">Roman Emperor Julian the Apostate</a> ordered the body to be dug up, burned, and his ashes scattered across the fields.</p>\n\n            <figure>\n              <picture><source sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-280.webp 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-380.webp 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-480.webp 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-640.webp 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-840.webp 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-1280.webp 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-1600.webp 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-1920.webp 1920w\" type=\"image/webp\"><img src=\"/docs/saint-jean/incendie-640.jpg\" title=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the central panel, “the body of John the Baptist dug up and burned on the order of Emperor Julian the Apostate”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" alt=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the central panel, “the body of John the Baptist dug up and burned on the order of Emperor Julian the Apostate”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" class=\"class-diane-img\" width=\"619\" height=\"1427\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-280.jpg 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-380.jpg 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-480.jpg 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-640.jpg 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-840.jpg 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-1280.jpg 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-1600.jpg 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/incendie-1920.jpg 1920w\"></picture><figcaption>detail of the central panel, “the body of John the Baptist dug up and burned on the order of Emperor Julian the Apostate”</figcaption>\n            </figure>\n\n\n\n            <h6 class=\"yellow\">Detail of the wall in which the head of John the Baptist is hidden, inner central panel</h6>\n\n              <p>His head appears lower down in <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">the opening of the wall</span>, behind <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">a stone</span>.</p>\n\n              <p>But things do not go as planned.</p>\n              <p>According to legend, the head was buried separately by <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">a potter from the city of Emesse</span>, the present <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homs\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homs\" id=\"homs\" class=\"yellow\"><ruby lang=\"en\">Homs<rp>(</rp><rt lang=\"ar\">حمص</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></a> in Syria, and then is thought to have appeared to Saint Marcellus who discovered it by following a star <span style=\"color: #999;\">(<cite>The Golden Legend</cite> chapter 121, paragraph III.)</span>.</p>\n\n            <figure>\n              <picture><source sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-280.webp 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-380.webp 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-480.webp 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-640.webp 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-840.webp 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-1280.webp 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-1600.webp 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-1920.webp 1920w\" type=\"image/webp\"><img src=\"/docs/saint-jean/mur-640.jpg\" title=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the central panel, “the head of John the Baptist in the opening of a wall”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" alt=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the central panel, “the head of John the Baptist in the opening of a wall”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" class=\"class-40-img\" width=\"603\" height=\"1030\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-280.jpg 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-380.jpg 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-480.jpg 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-640.jpg 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-840.jpg 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-1280.jpg 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-1600.jpg 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/mur-1920.jpg 1920w\"></picture><figcaption>detail of the central panel, “the head of John the Baptist in the opening of a wall”</figcaption>\n            </figure>\n            \n              <p>Thus ends the account of the legend of John the Baptist according to <cite>The Golden Legend</cite>.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n</article>"
}